snippet.textDisplay: Will we ever dig a little deeper and truly look for answers? During the few clips I've seen of fellow 'celebrities' mourning and remembering, I can't help trying, it's just in my nature...So when so called celebrities implore the public to exercise kindness, should they perhaps be asking themselves another question?: In a day and age where they fly around in corporate jets, are chauffeured around in limousines, to areas of London where most of us couldn't afford a cup of tea, is the jealously that manifests as online abuse somewhat understandable? Even 50-years ago, the gap between the haves and have nots was so much less, and now, with the gap wider than ever, every minute of their lives are broadcast through social media on a minute-to-minute basis. I can't help thinking that there's something badly wrong with this entire picture. The fact that a young woman ended her own life, that the media made her existence a misery, and that the public is so consumed by it all. If the general public's life, on average, was so more meaningful, so more fulfilling, with less scarcity and material possessions bought on credit, I believe most would be less inclined to even pay attention, much less pass judgement and ridicule.

snippet.textDisplay: My heart goes out to her and her family who must be bereft. She was charged and was due to appear in court due to a law change that was designed to protect women. In the old days usually a female domestic abuse victim would be badly hurt by her partner but her reluctance and fear to testify in court  meant that no charges would be filed and the police would have to walk away from these incidents or file a lesser breach of the peace charge. The new law was designed to allow the police to charge without the injured party pressing charges and take it out of the injured parts hands. This law could not be overlooked just because the attacker was A. A Woman. B. A public figure. C Attractive. The poor girl probably knew that the evidence against her was damning and she would be convicted of assault. I don't believe she would have recieved a prison sentence but it would probably have meant that any TV work would be impossible as our cancel culture and lack of redemptive empathy would consign her to obscurity. I hope she is at peace.
